I know that Blazor currently uses a registered function approach, but I'm not sure why exactly this is required. I think It'd be nice if we could call arbitrary JavaScript functions without having to register them first. 

I have implemented a simple workaround for this. Please take a look and let me know if this something that you may want to implement (of course in a proper way) in Blazor. If not, can you please tell me why it's a bad idea and is there any reason for me not to use this approach?

In my implementation, I have a C# helper method called `JavaScriptInterop.Invoke` which can be used like this:
```csharp
// Call console.log without registering it
// JS call: console.log({"str": "Hello", "f": 1.23, "b": false});
// returns null
JavaScriptInterop.Invoke<object>("console.log", new { str = "Hello", f = 1.23, b = false });

// Method with variable number of params
// JS call: Math.max(3, 4.3, 5.1);
// returns 5.1
JavaScriptInterop.Invoke<double>("Math.max", 3, 4.3, 5.1);

// Access properties (doesn't have to be method call)
// JS call: Math.PI
// returns: 3.141592653589793
JavaScriptInterop.Invoke<double>("Math.PI");

// Invalid reference
// JS call: doesn't call anything
// returns null
JavaScriptInterop.Invoke<object>("invalid.ref");
```

And here's how I implemented it
* Helper method `JavaScriptInterop.Invoke` to call registered JS function `invokeUnregistered`
```csharp
public static class JavaScriptInterop
{
    public static TRes Invoke<TRes>(string identifier, params object[] args)
    {
        return RegisteredFunction.Invoke<TRes>("invokeUnregistered", new { identifier, args });
    }
}
```
* Registering a generic JS function invoker `invokeUnregistered`
```html
<script type="blazor-boot"></script>
<script>
    Blazor.registerFunction('invokeUnregistered', data => {
        var ref = data.identifier
            .split('.')
            .reduce((prev, curr) => prev && prev[curr], window);
        return ref instanceof Function ?
            ref.apply(null, data.args) :
            ref;
    });
</script>
```


PS: This could also be implemented as a dynamic class, so that the call will look something like this:
```csharp
//this will be translated to JavaScriptInterop.Invoke<double>("Math.max", 1, 2, 3);
var max = JavaScript.Math.max(1, 2, 3).As<double>();
```

I have been playing with cascading dropdown lists, and have noticed that the dependent dropdown retains the selectedIndex value when the primary dropdown option is changed and the dependent is populated with a different set of options. I have used both the `bind` syntax and the `onchange` option with the same result.

